He held that it would be time enough to judge 
how Julia would take it after they had thrown up 
the place ; and he made it his duty to see that his 
mother should address to Mrs. Dallow, by letter, 
a formal notification of their retirement. Mrs. 
Dallow could protest then if she liked. Nick 
was aware that, in general, he was not practical ; 
he could imagine why, from his early years, 
people should have joked him about it. But this 
time he was determined that his behavior should 
be founded on a rigid view of things as they 
were. He did n t see his mother s letter to Julia, 
but he knew that it went. He thought she would 
have been more loyal if she had shown it to him, 
though of course there could be but little ques 
tion of loyalty now. That it had really been 
written, however, very much on the lines he dic 
tated, was clear to him from the subsequent sur 
prise which Lady Agnes s blankness did not pre 
