brother, but Miriam stopped her, saying it did n t 
matter ; besides, Dashwood was telling Nick 
something something they wanted him to 
know. "We re in a great excitement he has 
taken a theatre," Miriam added. 

" Taken a theatre ? " Biddy was vague. 

"We re going to set up for ourselves. He s 
going to do for me altogether. It has all been 
arranged only within a day or two. It remains 
to be seen how it will answer," Miriam smiled. 
Biddy murmured some friendly hope, and her in 
terlocutress went on : " Do you know why I Ve 
broken in here to-day, after a long absence in 
terrupting your poor brother, taking up his pre 
cious time ? It s because I m so nervous." 

" About your first night ? " Biddy risked. 

" Do you know about that are you com 
ing? " Miriam asked quickly. 

" No, I m not coming I have n t a place." 

" Will you come if I send you one ? " 

"Oh, but really, it s too beautiful of you!" 
stammered the girl. 

" You shall have a box ; your brother shall 
bring you. You can t squeeze in a pin, I m told ; 
but I ve kept a box, I 11 manage it. Only, if 
I do, you know, mind you come ! " Miriam 



 867 

exclaimed, in suppliance, resting her hand on 
Biddy s. 

" Don t be afraid. And may I bring a friend 
the friend with whom I m staying ? " 

Miriam looked at her. " Do you mean Mrs. 
Dallow?" 

" No, no Miss Tressilian. She puts me up, 
she has got a flat. Did you ever see a flat ? " 
asked Biddy expansively. " My cousin s not in 
London." Miriam replied that she might bring 
whom she liked, and Biddy broke out, to her 
